Later, after the meeting dissolved, Ren found me on a balcony that shouldn't exist.

"Quite a day, huh?" Ren said.

I laughed—manic edge. "Understatement. I just met twelve immortal mystics who told me I might be some prophesied savior. So yeah. Quite a day."

Silence. The city hummed below.

Ren's heart was hammering. Three years of deception pressing down. *Tell him NOW.*

"Chris, there's something I need to tell you."

Something in his tone made me turn fully. "What?"

"Three years ago, Tao came to me with an assignment."

I waited. Silent.

"He'd identified a potential Pattern. Said I should find him. Be his friend." Ren forced himself to meet my eyes. "I was sent to find you. Our meeting wasn't coincidence. I knew who you were before we met."

The silence had weight. Physical pressure.

"You're telling me our entire friendship was an assignment?"

"No. Yes. Fuck." Ren ran his hand through his hair. "I was assigned to be near you. But everything else—the friendship, the late-night talks about the Dodgers—that was REAL. That was MY choice."

"How am I supposed to believe that? Maybe you're just really good at your job."

The accusation hit like a blow. "You were a mission for about three months. Then you became my friend. My actual, genuine, *chosen* friend. The mission was proximity. Everything I felt after that—that was choice."

"Three years, Ren. THREE YEARS you've been lying."

"I wasn't lying about loving you like a brother. I wasn't lying about giving a shit when your grandmother died. I wasn't lying when I said you mattered." Ren's voice broke. "I was lying about how we met. About why I was there. And I'm sorry. I'm so fucking sorry, Chris."

Long silence. Ren let it sit.

Finally, I spoke, voice small: "Did Tao tell you to say all that too? Is this part of the manipulation?"

The question landed like a knife.

"No. God, no. This is me, risking everything, telling you the truth because you DESERVE it. Even if it means you hate me. Even if I lose you." He paused. "I was sent to find you. I chose to love you. Both things are true."

"I don't know if I can trust you."

"I know."

"I don't know if I can forgive this."

"I know."

"But I also don't know if I can do this without you." My voice cracked. "Is that fucked up?"

"It's human." Ren moved carefully. "I don't expect forgiveness. I don't expect trust. I'm not going anywhere. Assignment or not, you're stuck with me. Unless you tell me to leave."

